According to "Miyakojima Kijishitsugi," a mid-18th-century compilation of myths and folklore from Miyako Island, Koi-tsuno requested the Heavenly Emperor to become the island's guardian deity. The Heavenly Emperor blessed him, broke off the tip of the [[Ama-no-Iwato]] and cast it into the ocean, forming Miyako Island. Koi-tsuno then descended with the goddess Koitama to the site of the present-day Utaki, where they gave birth to many gods and ensured the prosperity of the island's people<ref>{{DOClink|[http://www.kisc.meiji.ac.jp/~meikodai/datebasa/miyakojima_kijisitsugi.doc Miyakojima Kijishitsugi]}} Meiji University Institute of Japanese Ancient Studies</ref>.

